Plymouth WI Schools
July 21 at 8:03 PM ·

Horizon Elementary recently got a new compost bin for its Golden Garden! Thanks to Tony Peterson for building it, Evergreen Pallets for donating the wood, & Parents and Teachers for Horizon (P.A.T.H.) for purchasing it for the school. Third-grade teacher Jackie Murphy has started another native pollinators garden; the monarchs are loving the all the milkweed!
text:
Plymouth WI Schools
July 21 at 8:03 PM ·

Horizon Elementary recently got a new compost bin for its Golden Garden! Thanks to Tony Peterson for building it, Evergreen Pallets for donating the wood, & Parents and Teachers for Horizon (P.A.T.H.) for purchasing it for the school. Third-grade teacher Jackie Murphy has started another native pollinators garden; the monarchs are loving the all the milkweed!

post_text: Way to go Horizon!!
shared_text:
Plymouth WI Schools
July 16 at 7:22 PM ·

Horizon Elementary School collected 57 gallons of can tabs for the Ronald McDonald House – surpassing its goal for the 2019-20 school year of 50 gallons, even though school was closed in March. The collection was organized by Horizon custodian Deb Eder and collected by retired Horizon aide Cindy Lorenz & her husband, Burnie, who retired from the district maintenance staff. The Lorenzes, who have collected about 14,000 gallons of tabs over the years, said: “We want to thank Horizon Elementary School and families for collecting can tabs for our camping group!”

post_text:
The show must go on! No school, no problem! The 27th annual Horizon talent show has gone virtual! Share your talent with your friends online!

Talents showcased may include, but are not limited to: singing, dancing, instrumental music, skits, magic, comedy, gymnastics, martial arts, hula hooping, you name it! Be as creative as you want! Just make sure your act is appropriate and family friendly, and uses appropriate social distancing if friends outside your family are involved.

Videos will need to be no more than three minutes long, and can be sent to horizonpath411@gmail.com. Please send them by Monday, April 20th. Our Virtual Talent Show will then be held on the Horizon Has Heart website in the next few weeks. We will let you know when the show is ready to go!

We can’t wait to see your talents, quarantine style!

Hi All, It is Mrs. Budrecki.
First, I miss everyone so much!

The teachers and I have been working on some fun projects for you to enjoy. Here is a webpage created for our Horizon family to explore and have fun! http://hzhasheart.weebly.com/. If we can't see each other at school, we wanted to create a space where we can still be connected.

Another activity I have is... Where in the World is Mrs. Budrecki? Each day you will get some clues to figure out where I am. At the end of the week, I will share where I virtually visit so you can virtually visit that location too! I sent the clue to your Google Classroom and 5K and 1st grade your teachers will be sending you the clue within the next day.

Horizon has 3 entries in the Wisconsin Bonnie Plant Cabbage Contest:
Eden 7lb. 2oz.
Hunter 7lb 7oz
Draco 10lb
Ayden 12 lb. 2 oz

Cabbage seedlings were delivered to Horizon in the spring and sent home with all 3rd graders. Students take care of them during the summer and then weigh the harvested cabbage. They also submit a photo.

A winner will be randomly chosen from all state entries for a $1,000 scholarship. Winners will be announced in December.
https://bonniecabbageprogram.com/

School Fundraiser Information: This semester, Horizon is participating in a unique fundraising program with Art to Remember that gives you the opportunity to purchase keepsake items with your child's artwork on them. The best part is that every keepsake order supports our school.

Order forms for Art to Remember have been sent home with students last week and are due back by November 16th. You can also conveniently order online with your child’s personalized code from the order form. To see available keepsake items like coffee mugs, key chains, and necklaces, or to order visit https://arttoremember.com/fundraising-programs/keepsake-programs/products/

A great summer activity... visit the Plymouth Public Library for the Animal Quest—Live animals this Wednesday, June 27- Two shows—10:00 am and 1:30 pm.

Animal Quest rescues animals in need and educates audiences across the Midwest. They have a wide variety of mammals, reptiles, birds, and amphibians. Ten of these animals will visit the Plymouth Public Library. Come learn about these amazing creatures! Seating available first-come-first-served.

post_text:
Third graders have been all about Wisconsin products and field to fork.

Thursday students visited Barbara Zimmermann's Drewry Maple Farm and found out how sap is collected and how it becomes syrup.

The FFA visited and classes made butter and taste tested dried cranberries and 4 varieties of cheeses.

The Spudmobile visited and students learned about how Wisconsin is a leader in our country's potato production. #HZ3rdgraders
